    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  Vaccines and first-generation antiviral therapeutics have provided important protection against coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). However, there remains a need for additional therapeutic options that provide enhanced efficacy and protection against potential viral resistance. The SARS-CoV-2 papain-like protease (PL\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  ) is one of two essential cysteine proteases involved in viral replication. While inhibitors of the SARS-CoV-2 main protease (M\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  ) have demonstrated clinical efficacy, known PL\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  inhibitors have to date lacked the inhibitory potency and requisite pharmacokinetics to demonstrate that targeting PL\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  translates to\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  efficacy in a preclinical setting. Herein, we report the machine learning-driven discovery of potent, selective, and orally available SARS-CoV-2 PL\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  inhibitors, with lead compound PF-07957472 (\n                  <jats:bold>4</jats:bold>\n                  ) providing robust efficacy in a mouse-adapted model of COVID-19 infection.\n                </jats:p>",
